{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:06:47.844Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Mock Users**\n\nI've defined mock users for testing the API. Specifically, `s.vance@governance.gff.ai` with the `gff_admin` role and `VanceSecure2026!` as the password, alongside `a.mercer@apex-sovereign.gff.ai` as `client_admin` and `MercerSecure2026!` as its password.\n\n\n**Mapping Roles to Users**\n\nI'm now mapping roles to specific API mock users. I've added `e.carter@global-retail.gff.ai` as `client_admin` and `m.vance@sovereign-logistics.gff.ai` as a potentially inactive `client_member` to the list. I've also identified `s.jenkins@fed-treasury.gff.ai` with the `client_member` role. I'm focusing on how these users can be pre-filled based on the role switchers.\n\n\n**Clarifying Backend Availability**\n\nI'm now clarifying how to check backend availability within `handleAuthenticate` in `SecureLogin.tsx`. I think a call to `/api/v1/auth/login` with credentials should suffice. Upon success, I'll store the `accessToken` locally, with a clear note to address security for production. Then, a call to `/api/v1/auth/me` will follow.\n\n\n**Implementing User Session Retrieval**\n\nI'm now implementing `Authorization: Bearer <accessToken>` to load the current user. I realize the `/api/v1/auth/me` response contains the data for the user session object and should be stored in `localStorage` under `gff_ai_preview_session_v1`. It seems the `/app/portal/layout.tsx`, `/app/admin/layout.tsx`, and `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` already read from this key! I've confirmed that storing the `/api/v1/auth/me` response under `gff_ai_preview_session_v1` will automatically feed the correct, real user session to the existing routing logic, which feels robust!\n\n\n**Refining Session Handling**\n\nI'm refining session handling. If I store the `/api/v1/auth/me` response in `gff_ai_preview_session_v1`, it aligns perfectly with the `PreviewSession` structure, including `name`, `email`, `role`, and `clearance`. I plan to set `isMock: false`, so `getPreviewSession` can accommodate both mock and real sessions. I'm also considering API POST request failure scenarios, especially validation errors and backend unavailability, so I know I need a dev fallback for these cases!\n\n\n**Implementing Fallback Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing a clear fallback mechanism for the role preview when the backend is unavailable or the login fails. The basic flow starts with a POST to `/api/v1/auth/login`.  I'm focusing on handling both network errors and server-side validation, gracefully falling back to a mock role preview if necessary, especially if no backend route is served. The fallback will be clearly labelled.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Secure Storage**\n\nI'm now prioritizing secure storage instead of `localStorage` to mitigate XSS risks and prevent JWT token leakage. I'll store the access token and the user session retrieved from `/api/v1/auth/me`. I am planning to fetch user info via `/api/v1/auth/me` and storing session data appropriately.\n\n\n**Addressing Authentication Logic**\n\nI'm now focusing on a critical edge case for authentication: what if credentials provided match a preview role but the API is available? I realize if someone tries `preview-gff-admin@internal.gff.ai` while the backend *is* available, the login will fail. I'm ensuring this is handled gracefully.\n\n\n**Visualizing Auth Server Status**\n\nI'm now implementing the UI updates. I want a clear visual indicator on the login page showing the **Secure Enclave Auth API** status. I'm focusing on messages like \"Connected\" or \"Dev Preview Fallback Mode\".  I'll start with a check or ping, and fetch `/api/v1/auth/me` on mount to check the current authentication status.\n\n\n**Visualizing Auth Backend Status**\n\nI'm now implementing the UI for auth backend status visualization. My plan is to use a green pulsing badge for \"AUTH SERVICE: ACTIVE (Zero-Trust API Mode)\" when the backend is online, and amber/yellow for \"AUTH SERVICE: OFFLINE (Dev Preview Fallback)\" otherwise. I'm testing `fetch(\"/api/v1/auth/login\")` for responsiveness to check availability.\n\n\n**Testing Backend API Availability**\n\nI'm now testing the API availability via empty POST requests to the `/api/v1/auth/login` endpoint to catch 400 status. The 400 proves that the API route is running and configured, a key indicator for testing authentication and for running the application. Now, I will look into the default roles list.\n\n\n**Populating Quick Role Selectors**\n\nI'm now populating quick role selectors. I'm pre-filling valid backend user credentials from the `API_MOCK_USERS` when their role is selected.  For roles that are only in the mock preview database, I'll be pre-filling their corresponding preview credentials instead.\n\n\n**Integrating User Role Selection**\n\nI'm now integrating new user roles! I'm adding `support_agent` with email `preview-support-agent@internal.gff.ai` and `viewer` with `preview-viewer@internal.gff.ai`. When the backend is online, clicking \"Authenticate Gateway\" with admin credentials will succeed with a valid API call. If the backend fails, the app falls back to mock roles with a clean label. This approach looks great!\n\n\n**Refining UI State Indicators**\n\nI'm now refining the UI state indicators, adding a banner to the login page to clearly show the authentication system's status. It will display \"Active\" or \"Fallback\" with a clean visual style. I plan to use this to show both backend and session availability on the login page in the MVP login flow.\n\n\n"}}
